I had a very full weekend, and so I was not at my computer much.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#WCACs was Saturday, consuming my day from early (for a Saturday)\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#until fairly late (I got home around 8:30-9pm). It was a well\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#spent day, though PVI did not do as well as they could have.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#Many of our guys didn't seem to have their heads in the matches,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#and our performance reflected that. Still, we had four guys\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#in finals, and several more took third. Unfortunately our heavy\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#weight was injured in his final match, I have not heard officially,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#hopefully they were mistake, but the trainers think he broke his\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#collar bone, which would put him out for St. Alban's and states.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#I have to feel sorry for both him and the team. Michael did well,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#but not great. He lost his first match, in which he could have done\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#better, won his second match decisively, and then lost his third.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#He lost to the wrestlers who took first and third respectively,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#but my impression, having wrestled myself, having watched my team,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#William and his team, and now Michael and his team, is that Michael\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#could have won at least one of those, especially that match against\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#Good Council (the first one).   
\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#Sunday I went to St. Veronica's 10:15am mass. I must say that it\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#is nice being able to leave at approximately 10:05 and get their at\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#10:13, though I am aware that this is not something to depend on\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#(I didn't hit a red light at the Fairfax County Parkway), and I\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#would of course like to get there earlier most of the time anyway.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#It is also nice to have an instructive homily. Many times you\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#are confronted with the seeming dichotomy between sequestering\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#your faith from the sight of others and being "Holier than thou"\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#(as my Mom would say), the kind of person who no one much likes who\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#may or may not live their faith well, but who, regardless, tries to\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#push their faith in your face. It is an easy trap to fall into,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#on either side. Addressing the side that is, I think, more of a\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#danger for me, we are called to be missionaries, to work for the\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#conversion of others, we **must** be demonstrative in\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#our faith, people around us **must** know that we are\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#Catholic, and our lives ***must*** be such that\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#they will be drawn towards that faith. Fr. Pollard (spelling?) gave\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#some advice on threading that needle. We must do what is required\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#for our own welfare, praying before meals, even in restaurants,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#and even when around people who wouldn't. We need not pray aloud.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#We must provide for the needs of those dependent on us, parents must\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#share their experience with God enough to provide a concrete example\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#for their children not just of ritual and tradition, but of life and\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#the meaning of faith in it. Beyond that, we must