\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#Later Sunday I went to Chris and John's Super Bowl Party. I haven't\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#ever done this before, I haven't even *watched* football in\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#ages, almost certainly not since my father died. I do not know\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#that I would go again. I was strongly reminded of why I dislike\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#football. It is such a pointless game at a professional level.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#And seems so silly to me as a wrestler anyway. I know that there\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#are, must be people, who feel the same way about wrestling, but\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#emotions are nothing if not subjective. I am reminded of the times\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#football players have attended their first wrestling practice.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#None of them has found themselves prepared by the fall season of\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#football for the rigors of wrestling, even though a football game\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#is *much* longer than a wrestling match. And the difference\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#in practice is not in vain, the wrestling match, I have been told,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#even by a good football player, requires more in 6 minutes than the\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#football game does. Regardless, football strikes me as a bunch\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#of "dumb jocks" (intentionally invoking the stereotype) slamming\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#into each other with occasional displays of skill (some running\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#and catching, some throwing contain skill). The displays that the\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#players create only serve to reinforce this position. The dancing\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#after a touch down or a good play especially seems out of place,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#excessive, crass. Wrestling is not entirely immune from this,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#after a pin, you will often see arms raised in victory, a bellow as\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#emotion is released. It is to some extent inherent in competitive\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#personalities, and so I think it is the excess and silliness\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#of the football display that disgusts, not its presence alone.\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#Let us not forget, also, that the wrestling match begins and ends\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#with a hand shake, wrestlers are required to walk onto and off of\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#the mat as gentlemen, and few football players appear to attempt\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#to be gentlemen. It is interesting as a side note that we respect\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#less the DeMatha wrestlers, who do not meet our (PVI's) standards,\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#as compared to other schools we wrestle, even though DeMatha is\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#unquestionably one of the very best, and consistently one of the\#$NEWLINE-MARKER$\#very best, schools we wrestle.





